Create the Directory and Project
Run these commands to set up the workspace:

PowerShell
# Create the root folder
mkdir C:\Users\Kavana\Experiment8
cd C:\Users\Kavana\Experiment8

# Create the standard Maven structure
mkdir -p src\main\java\com\lab
2. Create the Necessary Files
You need a basic pom.xml and a Java file so Jenkins has something to build.

A. Create the Java File:
Run notepad src\main\java\com\lab\App.java and paste:

Java
package com.lab;
public class App {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Jenkins Auto-Trigger Test!");
    }
}
B. Create the pom.xml:
Run notepad pom.xml and paste:

XML
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/maven-v4_0_0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>
  <groupId>com.lab</groupId>
  <artifactId>experiment-8</artifactId>
  <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
</project>
3. Connect to GitHub (The "SCM" Part)
Before configuring Jenkins, your folder must become a Git repository.

Go to GitHub.com and create a new repository named exp-8-trigger.

Run these commands in your terminal:

PowerShell
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git branch -M master
git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/exp-8-trigger.git
git push -u origin master
4. Configure Jenkins Build Triggers
Now, we tell Jenkins to watch that GitHub repository.

Create Job: In Jenkins, click New Item -> Freestyle Project -> Name it AutoTriggerJob.

Source Code Management: Select Git and paste your GitHub URL.

Build Triggers (The Task):

Check Poll SCM.

In the Schedule box, type: * * * * * (This means check for changes every 1 minute).

Build Steps: Select Invoke top-level Maven targets and set the Goal to clean package.

Save.

5. The Outcome: Automatic Triggering
To prove it works, you must make a change to your code and see Jenkins react without you touching it.

Modify Code: notepad src\main\java\com\lab\App.java. Add a comment like // Trigger Test. Save and exit.

Push Change:

PowerShell
git add .
git commit -m "Testing auto-trigger"
git push origin master
